### Higher-Order Components (HOC)

A higher-order component is a function that takes a component and returns a new enhanced component. HOCs are a pattern for reusing component logic, predating hooks.

---

### Basic HOC Pattern

```jsx
function withLogger(WrappedComponent) {
  return function EnhancedComponent(props) {
    console.log('Rendering:', WrappedComponent.name);
    return <WrappedComponent {...props} />;
  };
}

const EnhancedButton = withLogger(Button);
```

### Common HOC Examples

```jsx
// Loading state HOC
function withLoading(WrappedComponent) {
  return function WithLoading({ isLoading, ...props }) {
    if (isLoading) return <Spinner />;
    return <WrappedComponent {...props} />;
  };
}

// Auth guard HOC
function withAuth(WrappedComponent) {
  return function WithAuth(props) {
    const { user } = useAuth();
    if (!user) return <Navigate to="/login" />;
    return <WrappedComponent {...props} user={user} />;
  };
}
```

### Composition

```jsx
const EnhancedComponent = withAuth(withLogger(withLoading(MyComponent)));
```

### HOC vs Hooks

| Aspect | HOC | Hooks |
|--------|-----|-------|
| Pattern | Wraps component | Function composition |
| Code reuse | Yes | Yes |
| Naming conflicts | Risk with prop names | No conflicts |
| Complexity | Higher (wrapper hell) | Lower |
| Modern preference | Legacy | Recommended |

> **Key Point:** Hooks are the modern replacement for most HOC patterns. However, HOCs are still used for third-party libraries (connect in Redux, withRouter, withStyles). Understand HOCs to maintain legacy codebases.

